s the evolution of the dime museum from its eighteenth-century inception as a "cabinet of curiosities" to its death at the hands of new amusement technologies in the early twentieth century. From big theaters which accommodated audiences of three thousand to meager converted storefronts exhibiting petrified wood and living anomalies, this study vividly reanimates the array of museums, exhibits, and performances that make up this entertainment institution. Tracing the scattered legacy of the dime museum from vaudeville theater to Ripley's museum to the talk show spectacles of today, Dennett makes a significant contribution to the history of American popular entertainment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCuriosities and wondersxMuseumszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aDime museumszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aEccentrics and eccentricitiesxMuseumszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMuseumszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPopular culturezUnited StatesxHistory. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh  aWeird.  aWonderful.  aamusement.  acabinet.  acentury.  achronicles.  acuriosities.  adeath.  adime.  aearly.  aeighteenth-century.  aevolution.  afrom.  ahands.  ainception.  amuseum.  atechnologies.  atwentieth.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000z97831107169240 cprintz978081471885840uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814744215.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814744215423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814744215/original  a978-3-11-071692-4  New York University Press Archive eBook-Package Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPD